>Are you implying the POSSIBILITY, at least, that DES and IDEA, when used
>together, might form a "group" that could be WEAKER than either alone?  Yes,
>it's obvious that it's "not either", but I think that was the main premise
>for interleaving the two in the first place.
>
In both DES and IDEA, subsequent rounds build on each other.  Interleaving
one DES round with one IDEA round might disrupt some of the properties of
IDEA and DES: avalanche effect, etc.

This is to say nothing of interleaving 16-round DES with 8-round IDEA.

Bruce
